Q: Given the sentence "A girl is sitting in a chair and looking at something." can we conclude that "A girl is sitting and looking at something."?
Options:
(I). yes;
(II). it is not possible to tell;
(III). no;
A: yes
Explain how we arrive at this answer:
The answer is yes because the original sentence states "A girl is sitting in a chair and looking at something." This implies that she is sitting and looking at something. The second sentence, "A girl is sitting and looking at something," is a simplified version of the first sentence that still conveys the same meaning. So, it is correct to say that the answer is yes
